        <div xml:id="AN14-kilavi"></div>
        <div xml:id="AN14">
            <lg type="edition"><l>arakkat taṉṉa cennilap peruvaḻik</l>
<l>kāyāñ cemma ṟāayp palavuṭa</l>
<l>ṉīyaṉ mūtāy parappap <choice><seg>pavaḷamoṭu</seg><seg>pavaḻamoṭu</seg></choice></l>
<l>maṇimiṭain taṉṉa kuṉṟaṅ kavaiiya</l>
<l>vaṅkāṭ <choice><seg>ṭāriṭai</seg><seg>ṭavariṭai</seg></choice> maṭappiṇai taḻīit</l>
<l>tirimarup piralai pullarun tukaḷu</l>
<l>mullai viyaṉpulam parappik kōvalar</l>
<l>kuṟumpoṟai maruṅki <choice><seg>ṉiṟumpū</seg><seg>ṉaṟumpū</seg></choice> <choice><seg>tayarap</seg><seg>vayarap</seg></choice></l>
<l>patavumēya laruntu matavunaṭai nallāṉ</l>
<l>vīṅkumāṇ cerutta ṟīmpāl <choice><seg>piliṟṟak</seg><seg>piliṟṟik</seg></choice></l>
<l><choice><seg>kaṉṟupayil</seg><seg>kaṉṟu</seg></choice> <choice><seg>kura<supplied>la</supplied></seg><seg>payirkuraṉ</seg></choice> maṉṟunirai <choice><seg>pukutaku</seg><seg>pukutaru</seg></choice></l>
<l>mālaiyu muḷḷā rāyiṟ kālai</l>
<l>yāṅkā kuvaṅkol pāṇa veṉṟa</l>
<l>maṉaiyōḷ colletir collal cellēṉ</l>
<l>cevvaḻi nalyā ḻicaiyiṉeṉ paiyeṉak</l>
<l>kaṭavuḷ vāḻttip paiyuṇ meynniṟut</l>
<l>tavartiṟañ <choice><seg>celvēṉ</seg><seg>celaveṉak</seg></choice> kaṇṭaṉeṉ yā<supplied>ṉē</supplied></l>
<l>viṭuvicaik kutirai vilaṅkupari muṭukak</l>
<l>kalporu <choice><seg>tiraṅkum</seg><seg>tiraṅku</seg></choice> pallār <choice><seg>nēmik</seg><seg>nēmi</seg></choice></l>
<l>kārmaḻai muḻakkicai kaṭukku</l>
<l>muṉainal lūraṉ puṉaineṭun tērē.</l></lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l><choice><seg>“If he does not even remember [us] in the evening,</seg><seg>when the herd enters the shed, with voices calling out for the calves,</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>	when the full herd is ready to enter the shed, [their] voices calling out for the</seg><seg>	drizzling sweet milk from [their] swelling, glorious udders,</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>		calves,</seg><seg>	good cows with strong gait who feed grazing on Patavu grass,</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>	as [their] swelling, glorious udders are drizzling with sweet milk,</seg><seg>	while the cowherds are busy with fragrant flowers on the side of small heights,</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>	good cows with strong gait who feed grazing on Patavu grass,</seg><seg>	the wide fields being spread with jasmine,</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>	while </seg><seg>	where </seg></choice> the <choice><seg>cowherds forget themselves in amazement on the side of small heights,</seg><seg>Iralai with twisted horns eats grass [and] leaps,</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>	the wide fields being spread with jasmine,</seg><seg>	embracing [its] youthful doe on its path through the pretty wilderness,</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>	where the Iralai with twisted horns eats grass [and] leaps,</seg><seg>...</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>	embracing [its] youthful doe on the difficult path through the pretty wilderness,</seg><seg>Praising the god gently, speaking with the sound of the good lute</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>	which is forked between hills like sapphires set close</seg><seg>[tuned in] in Cevvaḻi [and] weighing the sorrowful truth</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>	with corals, when white ants [and] cochineals are spreading [there],<note place="foot">The colour imagery of the first four lines is unclear. We have first red and then red and blue, probably the red ground, the insects on the trees and the blue hills, but how do the white ants come into the picture?</note></seg><seg>I myself have seen that it will go<note place="foot">Literally: “that [there is] going”.</note>, on his part,</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>	many together, being scattered </seg><seg>	the decorated </seg></choice> <choice><seg>on the eminence of ironwood trees</seg><seg>long chariot of the man from the good frontier village,</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>	on the big way in the ground red as vermilion,</seg><seg>	whose many-spoked wheels that sound when dashing over the stones</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>what will become of us in the morning, bard?”</seg><seg>	resemble the drumming noise of the monsoon rains,</seg></choice> </l>
<l><choice><seg>– I cannot </seg><seg></seg></choice> <choice><seg>answer [those] words from her in the house.</seg><seg>	while the horses advance in transverse motion, speed set free.</seg></choice> </l>
<l>Praising the god gently, speaking<note place="foot">icaiyiṉ eṉ: placed at the end of the cīr eṉ has to be accounted for.  We might take it, as above, as a verbal root eṉ “to say”, with a verbal root for an absolutive.  The only other option seems an awkwardly placed interrogative pronoun.</note> with the sound of the good lute</l>
<l>[tuned in] in Cevvaḻi [and] weighing the sorrowful truth</l>
<l>I will go to him. I myself have seen<note place="foot">cellēṉ...celvēṉ kaṇṭaṉeṉ yāṉē: here the actual sentence structure is doubtful. It is possible to read the first as a participial noun or even muṟṟeccam, and probably the last again as a muṟṟeccam (which is made likely by the post-positioned subject yāṉē), celvēṉ being the main verb in any case: “I, who have seen..., will go...” = “Since I have seen, I will go...”.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">	the decorated long chariot of the man from the good frontier village,</l>
<l rend="indent">	whose many-spoked wheels, that sound when dashing over the stones,</l>
<l rend="indent">	resemble the drumming noise of the monsoon rains,</l>
<l rend="indent">	while the horses advance in transverse motion, speed set free.</l>
<l rend="indent"></l></lg>
        </div>
